			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Petersburg</placeName> <date>June 12th 1854</date></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Enclosed I hand you<lb/> draft on <persName>Driscel<add>&#63;</add> &#38; Co</persName> your city for 151 47&#47;100 Dolls<lb/> being the amount paid in for your works<lb/> sent me&#44; and subscriptions to Occident&#8212;as pr<lb/> statement annexed&#8212;I have the remainder of<lb/> the books here&#8212;subject to your order&#8212;I do<lb/> not think the prospect of selling them here<lb/> is very good&#8212;however I will use my best<lb/> endeavours for your interest.  <persName>Sol Myers</persName> has<lb/> removed to <placeName>Richmond</placeName> &#38; I will send him his<lb/> Bible by first opportunity &#38; collect the amt.<lb/>  <persName>Mr Feldenheimer</persName> has removed to <placeName>Baltimore</placeName>.<lb/>  <persName>Mr Kating</persName> says he only took your Occident for<lb/> about four mos. and consequently did not pay<lb/> me.  <persName>Mr B. A. Davis</persName> declined purchasing the set<lb/> Prayer Books.  Doubtlessly you have thought me<lb/> very remiss in not attending to this matter before<lb/> <del>this</del>&#8212;and not without reason&#44; for a long time<lb/> has elapsed since the receipt of your letter&#8212;but<lb/> really the cares and duties of business have been<lb/> so very pressing as to leave me little leisure<lb/> to attend to any business entrusted to me</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>apart from my own.  Hoping my delay in<lb/> this affair has caused no serious inconvenience<lb/> or embarrassment on your part and best<lb/> wishes for your good health&#44; prosperity and<lb/> success I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)">Yours very Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">Michael M. Davis</persName></p>
